          "en": "I am lucky to have work."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "dl-balita",
      "word": "balita",
      "partOfSpeech": "noun",
      "translations": [
        "news",
        "information",
        "report"
      ],
      "relatedTagalog": "balita",
      "examples": [
        {
          "kp": "Meniglo ku king balita.",
          "en": "I was surprised by the news."
        },
        {
          "kp": "Atin balita king balen.",
          "en": "There is news in the town."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "dl-drayber",
      "word": "drayber",
      "partOfSpeech": "noun",
      "translations": [
        "driver"
      ],
      "relatedTagalog": "drayber",
      "examples": [
        {
          "kp": "Drayber ya ing lalaki.",
          "en": "The man is a driver."
        },
        {
          "kp": "Munta ya ing drayber king eskwela.",
          "en": "The driver goes to the school."
        }
      ],
      "notes": "English loanword from 'driver', spelled phonetically in Kapampangan and Tagalog. Common occupation term in modern Filipino languages."
    },
    {
      "id": "dl-temperatura",
      "word": "temperatura",
      "partOfSpeech": "noun",
      "translations": [
        "temperature"
      ],
      "relatedTagalog": "temperatura",
      "examples": [
        {
          "kp": "Mainit ya ing temperatura ngeni.",
          "en": "The temperature is high now."
        },
        {
          "kp": "Ano ya ing temperatura ngeni?",
          "en": "What is the temperature now?"
        }
      ],
      "notes": "Spanish loanword from 'temperatura', shared across Philippine languages. Used in weather reports and health contexts."
    }
  ],
